				\begin{document}$$\kappa_3 = \left[ 1+ \frac{1}{T} \int\limits_0^T \left( p_{g_i}\eta_{g_i}(t) - \frac{1}{T} \int\limits_0^T p_{g_i}\eta_{g_i}(t) dt \right)^2 dt \right]^{-2}$$\end{document}

In Eq. 15 the standard deviation is easily recognizable, with 1T∫0Tpgiηgi(t)dt\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{1}{T} \int_0^T p_{g_i}\eta_{g_i}(t)dt$$\end{document} representing the average power output of the generator from which to calculate the deviation. The inner square ensures that only positive deviations are summed, so that positive and negative deviations do not cancel each other out. The total deviation is increased by 1 so that κ3 approaches unity when the deviation with respect to the average power output approaches 0, e.g. when the gi has a constant power output. Since the standard deviation is a positive value, κ3 will also be a positive value with 0 < κ3 ≤ 1.

